# Auto-Tag Everything
# AI reads files and populates metadata columns automatically — turning a file dump into a filterable library.

[var: SITE = https://contoso.sharepoint.com/sites/demo/]
[var: LIBRARY = ${SITE}Project%20Documents/]
[category: Documents & Files]

[section: setup]

Creating the "Project Documents" library with metadata columns. If it already
exists from a previous run, Copilot will skip creation — just confirm the
columns and files are still in place.

[navigate: ${SITE}]

[open-chat]

[new-chat]

[prompt: Create a document library called "Project Documents". Add these columns: Department (Choice: Marketing, Finance, HR, Legal, Engineering), Document Type (Choice: Policy, Contract, Report, Presentation, Proposal), Confidentiality (Choice: Public, Internal, Confidential, Restricted), Summary (Multiple lines of text).]

[wait]

Now upload 6 sample files to the library — a mix of departments and types.
Good examples: an HR policy, a marketing proposal, a legal contract, a finance
report, an NDA, and a salary bands document. Files with real text content work
best since Copilot reads the actual text to infer the metadata.

[navigate: ${LIBRARY}]

[confirm: Upload 6 sample files to this library, then press Enter]

[new-chat]

Confirm 6 files are visible and ALL metadata columns (Department, Document
Type, Confidentiality, Summary) are blank before the demo.

[pause]

[section: demo]

[navigate: ${LIBRARY}]

Six files, zero metadata. This is what happens when you tell people to fill in
columns manually — they don't. The Department column is empty. The Document
Type column is empty. The Confidentiality column is empty. Nobody is going to
tag these by hand. So let's have AI do it.

[pause]

[open-chat]

[prompt: Read each file in this library. For every file, fill in the Department, Document Type, Confidentiality, and Summary columns based on the file's content.]

[wait]

Watch the columns fill in. Copilot read every document, figured out which
department owns it, what type of document it is, and how sensitive the content
is. Point out that it flagged the salary bands as Restricted and the NDA as
Confidential — it understood the sensitivity from the content, not from a label.

[pause]

Now let's see why metadata matters. Filter the library by Confidentiality
equals Confidential or Restricted.

[pause: Show the filtered view — 3 sensitive files surface instantly]

Two results. This filter was impossible 30 seconds ago because the metadata
didn't exist.

Now filter by Department equals Marketing.

[pause: Show Marketing filter — 2 files]

Two results. The marketing team now has a curated view without anyone manually
sorting anything. Metadata is the difference between a folder and a knowledge
base. The AI just built the knowledge base for you.

[screenshot: tools/screenshots/07-auto-tag-final.png]

[section: reset]

Clear all metadata values from the 6 files: set Department, Document Type,
Confidentiality, and Summary to blank for every row.

[navigate: ${LIBRARY}]

Edit each item and clear all four metadata columns, or use the grid view to
bulk-clear.

[new-chat]
